	<StaticContent title='Key Takeaways'>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<p>
					A personal balance sheet summarizes your assets (what you own) and
					liabilities (what you owe) in order to calculate your net worth.
				</p>
				<CallOut
					setColor={'green'}
					isCentered>
					<MathEq
						formula='\\text{Net worth} = \\text{What you own} - \\text{What you owe} = \\text{Assets} - \\text{Liabilities}'
					/>
				</CallOut>
				<li>
					<p>
						A personal cash flow statement measures your cash inflows (money you
						received) and your cash outflows (money you spent) to determine if
						you have a positive or negative net cash flow.
					</p>
					<CallOut
						setColor={'green'}
						isCentered>
						<MathEq
							formula='\\text{Net cash flow} = \\text{Cash inflow} - \\text{Cash outflows}'
						/>
					</CallOut>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Net cash flows can be used to decrease liabilities, which will
						increase net worth.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>Checking account: No interest, money for immediate use</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>Savings account: Low interest, money for short-term use</p>
				</li>
			</li>
		</ol>
